Text.Value: But. They weren't.

EditorData.NodeContext: Like a shrug. Not blaming them/ getting too down about it. It is what it is.

Text.Value: I miss you so much. But I'm happy. And getting up to some really important shit. Maybe you can see for yourselves. I don't know.

EditorData.NodeContext: Maybe looks up here, thinking about being watched by her folks from the afterlife.

Text.Value: It's the ultimate mystery. There are many possibilities, but we'll never know until we get there.
Me too. Didn't realise how nice it'd feel to come say hello.
You're with me here, anyway. Taters.

EditorData.NodeContext:
'Here' is in her heart.
In this moment 'Taters' means 'I love you' between Karlach and her family, which she is about to explain.

Text.Value: I was on my own after that. Fell in with Gortash not long after. If my folks had been alive, they would've sniffed him out straight away.
I agree with your dad. Death is the end of life - it's harsh, but true.
I'm glad we came here.
Leave.
May I ask how your parents died?
There was a lot of silly nonsense in our house. My mates used to say we had our own personal language. I guess I'm the last remaining speaker.
I was a teenager when mum passed - bad fever. A good healer could've saved her, but she slipped away before we found one who'd take our gold.
There is no need to wonder. Our souls travel to the City of Judgement and are then taken by the gods.
Mum used to say there was no such thing as death. That there was only change.
Dad went a few years later. He was on an errand for work, travelling the Risen Road. His cart overturned and caught him just so.
Something to look forward to. Bit morbid, but true all the same.
Meant 'I love you' in the Cliffgate household. I can't even remember how it started anymore. Lost family lore.
Here lie Pluck and Caerlack Cliffgate. My parents. Hi mum. Hi dad.

EditorData.NodeContext:
Warmly and with feeling, but not cracking/ tearing up
Caerlack = Karlach (spelled different, same sound)

Text.Value: Hopefully there's more waiting for me than that. Very hopefully.
Dad thought that was a load of woo. That gone meant gone, unless you'd struck a deal with one of the gods. Said he had better things to do in life than beg favours off immortals.
Your mum was right. Our bodies become soil, water, air. We don't die, we just change.
I'm not sure what I believe.
Nice thought, isn't it? This grass could be my mum's hair. The air in my lungs might be my dad telling me 'taters'. I like that.
'Taters'?
Classic Pluck Cliffgate. Harsh but honest. He may be right - but then again, he may not. Only one way to find out, huh?
Sorry I haven't visited. I've been... away. But I'm back now! And I brought friends.
If they deign to choose us. There's no guarantee, is there? And I've made little effort to attract the loyalty of anyone but you.

Synopsis: Karlach interacts with her parents tombstones. Throughout this convo she speaks with meaning, but doesn't get too emotional. Tenderness without a lot of sadness. She's had a long time to come to terms with the loss of her parents - this is more of a homecoming.
